WEBVTT

1
00:00:02.080 --> 00:00:05.960
My co-chair, Dr. Bob Vonderheide, and myself, we'd like to welcome you

2
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:09.990
to the Clinical Trials Plenary 3, Cellular Therapies

3
00:00:10.020 --> 00:00:13.340
and Complex Immunotherapies. We're really in for a treat

4
00:00:13.740 --> 00:00:16.440
with an interesting variety of clinical data this morning.

5
00:00:17.460 --> 00:00:21.040
We have CAR-Ts very early in the disease state in smoldering

6
00:00:21.050 --> 00:00:25.040
myeloma. We have novel CARs with early evidence of activity in

7
00:00:25.080 --> 00:00:29.000
refractory solid tumors. We have a bispecific antibody with a

8
00:00:29.020 --> 00:00:32.980
conditional 4-1BB agonist in MSS colorectal cancer

9
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:36.980
with clinical activity, especially at the higher doses of the 4-1BB ligand.

10
00:00:37.760 --> 00:00:41.540
And we have a novel vaccine targeting PD-L1 and IDO

11
00:00:41.680 --> 00:00:43.480
plus pembrolizumab for myeloma.

12
00:00:44.340 --> 00:00:48.100
Now I'm going to turn over the mic to my co-chair, Dr. Vonderheide.

13
00:00:49.620 --> 00:00:52.080
Thank you, James, and welcome everybody to the plenary session.

14
00:00:53.060 --> 00:00:55.960
I'm Bob Vonderheide. I'm the director of the Abramson Cancer Center at the

15
00:00:55.980 --> 00:00:57.820
University of Pennsylvania, and

16
00:00:59.100 --> 00:01:02.460
in two hours, I become president-elect of AACR.

17
00:01:02.700 --> 00:01:03.980
So pretty exciting year for me.

18
00:01:05.340 --> 00:01:05.640
Thank you.

19
00:01:07.640 --> 00:01:09.980
Thank you all for coming to the annual meeting. We'll jump right in.

20
00:01:10.020 --> 00:01:12.290
I'll introduce our first speaker, who is Dr.

21
00:01:12.540 --> 00:01:16.180
Omar Nadeem from the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, who will give us

22
00:01:16.260 --> 00:01:18.020
results of the CAR-PRISM trial.

23
00:01:27.120 --> 00:01:28.460
Thank you. Good morning, everyone.

24
00:01:29.820 --> 00:01:32.640
Thank you to the organizers for choosing our abstract for this plenary

25
00:01:32.650 --> 00:01:36.320
presentation. And on behalf of my co-investigator, it's my pleasure to share

26
00:01:36.360 --> 00:01:39.960
results of ciltacept gene autolysin in patients with high-risk smoldering

27
00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:42.180
myeloma, results from the CAR-PRISM trial.

28
00:01:43.790 --> 00:01:44.860
These are my disclosures.

29
00:01:46.640 --> 00:01:50.460
So high-risk smoldering myeloma is a precursor plasma cell neoplasm that carries

30
00:01:50.500 --> 00:01:54.480
approximately a 50% chance of progression to multiple myeloma in two years.

31
00:01:55.120 --> 00:01:58.460
And these patients are identified based on various previously published

32
00:01:58.480 --> 00:02:01.920
criteria. Historically, patients were placed on

33
00:02:01.980 --> 00:02:04.880
observation until they developed disease progression, at which point they would be

34
00:02:04.960 --> 00:02:06.600
offered myeloma induction therapy.

35
00:02:07.840 --> 00:02:11.460
In November of 2025, daratumumab, a CD38 monoclonal

36
00:02:11.540 --> 00:02:15.400
antibody, was the first agent approved by the US FDA for treatment for

37
00:02:15.420 --> 00:02:19.250
high-risk smoldering myeloma, and this was based on results from the Phase 3 AQUILA

38
00:02:19.360 --> 00:02:19.680
trial.

39
00:02:20.820 --> 00:02:24.440
In the AQUILA study, patients were randomized to either three years of daratumumab

40
00:02:24.500 --> 00:02:28.220
or active monitoring. And while daratumumab led to an improvement in

41
00:02:28.240 --> 00:02:31.200
progression-free and overall survival in this population,

42
00:02:31.820 --> 00:02:35.620
approximately 40% of patients still progressed at five years despite

43
00:02:35.630 --> 00:02:39.440
early interception with daratumumab, and rates of complete responses were

44
00:02:39.500 --> 00:02:40.790
low at less than 10%.

45
00:02:42.720 --> 00:02:45.740
And this trial is one of many management strategies that have been previously

46
00:02:45.800 --> 00:02:47.600
studied in patients with smoldering myeloma.

47
00:02:48.640 --> 00:02:52.040
Some of these has opted for the goal of disease control with low-intensity

48
00:02:52.120 --> 00:02:56.020
regimens, whereas others have gone for disease eradication with more

49
00:02:56.080 --> 00:02:59.320
high-potency regimens similar to what we give to multiple myeloma patients.

50
00:03:00.580 --> 00:03:04.500
Previous studies with lenalidomide and dexamethasone were also positive compared

51
00:03:04.540 --> 00:03:07.680
to active monitoring in patients with high-risk smoldering myeloma.

52
00:03:07.690 --> 00:03:10.960
And more recently, studies of triplets, quadruplets, and even stem cell

53
00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:14.829
transplantation have been studied in high-risk smoldering myeloma, leading to

54
00:03:14.860 --> 00:03:18.299
deeper responses and higher rates of MRD negative disease.

55
00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:23.040
However, achieving these deep responses unfortunately does not seem to have

56
00:03:23.420 --> 00:03:26.760
correlated with cure, as some of these patients still develop disease

57
00:03:26.820 --> 00:03:28.260
progression many years later.

58
00:03:29.760 --> 00:03:33.620
So we asked the question: Could the use of CAR T-cell therapy in an earlier disease

59
00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:37.300
state lead to disease eradication and the potential of cure at the

60
00:03:37.340 --> 00:03:39.100
time when the immune system is more intact?

61
00:03:40.860 --> 00:03:44.780
And this comes on the heels of the long-term follow-up from the CARTITUDE-1 trial,

62
00:03:44.820 --> 00:03:48.329
in which cilta-cel, a BCMA CAR T-cell therapy, was

63
00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:51.520
administered to heavily pretreated relapse refractory myeloma patients.

64
00:03:52.170 --> 00:03:56.140
And long-term follow-up of this study shows that approximately a third of patients

65
00:03:56.180 --> 00:04:00.080
are still progression free beyond five years, raising the possibility that

66
00:04:00.120 --> 00:04:03.940
this could be curative therapy, at least for a subset of relapse refractory

67
00:04:04.040 --> 00:04:04.880
myeloma patients.

68
00:04:06.640 --> 00:04:09.560
And if you look at the results from the CARTITUDE-4 trial, which looked at

69
00:04:09.580 --> 00:04:12.940
cilta-cel in even earlier disease states in one to three prior lines of

70
00:04:12.980 --> 00:04:16.860
therapy, and in patients that were lenalidomide refractory, this

71
00:04:16.899 --> 00:04:20.481
not only demonstrated improvement compared to standard of care regimens,

72
00:04:20.820 --> 00:04:24.320
but if you look at the Kaplan-Meier curves of survival compared to CARTITUDE-1

73
00:04:24.400 --> 00:04:28.220
study, earlier use of cilta-cel shows even better survival,

74
00:04:28.540 --> 00:04:32.340
suggesting that these therapies may yield even greater benefit if given in earlier

75
00:04:32.360 --> 00:04:32.950
disease states.

76
00:04:35.110 --> 00:04:37.500
So this was the hypothesis of our CAR-PRISM trial.

77
00:04:37.560 --> 00:04:41.300
We asked the question: Could the use of CAR T-cell therapy achieve MRD

78
00:04:41.310 --> 00:04:44.880
negative disease without any induction therapy in these high-risk patients?

79
00:04:45.860 --> 00:04:49.200
Our rationale was that the immune system is less altered in smoldering myeloma,

80
00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:52.960
and CAR T-cell therapy may have potentially even greater benefit compared to

81
00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:54.840
relapse refractory myeloma patients.

82
00:04:55.760 --> 00:04:59.660
We have some preliminary data from the bispecific T-cell engagers also targeting

83
00:04:59.680 --> 00:05:03.560
BCMA with teclistamab and linvoseltamab that have demonstrated high

84
00:05:03.620 --> 00:05:05.590
efficacy also in this population.

85
00:05:06.840 --> 00:05:10.040
In the high-risk smoldering myeloma state, the tumor burden is lower, and the

86
00:05:10.060 --> 00:05:12.060
plasma cells are less genomically complex.

87
00:05:12.120 --> 00:05:15.620
Therefore, we hypothesize that the efficacy may be enhanced and toxicities may

88
00:05:15.660 --> 00:05:19.280
be reduced. And this would allow for lack of exposure

89
00:05:19.620 --> 00:05:22.860
to standard of care induction regimens, which can then be deployed if patients

90
00:05:22.900 --> 00:05:24.820
develop myeloma progression in the future.

91
00:05:25.260 --> 00:05:29.240
And CAR T-cell therapy does have the potential to truly be one and done treatment

92
00:05:29.250 --> 00:05:31.300
for these patients to prevent myeloma in their lifetime.

93
00:05:33.100 --> 00:05:35.040
So here's the study design of the CAR-PRISM trial.

94
00:05:35.100 --> 00:05:38.840
Patients underwent screening and then had T-cell leukapheresis for CAR T-cell

95
00:05:38.900 --> 00:05:39.570
manufacturing.

96
00:05:40.420 --> 00:05:44.340
After this, eligible patients were offered the ability to undergo a stem cell

97
00:05:44.380 --> 00:05:48.110
collection to preserve their ability to have a transplant in the future if they

98
00:05:48.120 --> 00:05:49.210
develop disease progression.

99
00:05:50.280 --> 00:05:53.390
During the time of manufacturing, bridging therapy was not permitted.

100
00:05:53.940 --> 00:05:56.830
And then once the product was ready, patients received standard doses of

101
00:05:56.840 --> 00:06:00.700
lymphodepleting chemotherapy with cyclophosphamide and fludarabine, followed

102
00:06:00.740 --> 00:06:04.380
by a cilta-cel infusion on day one, and then were followed for safety and response

103
00:06:04.440 --> 00:06:08.252
assessments and remain in long-term follow-up.The primary

104
00:06:08.292 --> 00:06:11.332
endpoint of this study was safety, as assessed by incidence of dose-limiting

105
00:06:11.412 --> 00:06:14.932
toxicities, and key secondary endpoints included efficacy

106
00:06:15.012 --> 00:06:18.452
parameters such as overall response rate, complete response rates, MRD

107
00:06:18.492 --> 00:06:22.472
negativity, progression-free survival, and incidence and severity of AEs.

108
00:06:24.732 --> 00:06:27.052
Here's the inclusion criteria for the CAR PRISM trial.

109
00:06:27.562 --> 00:06:31.352
Patients were included if they met high risk criteria per the 20/2/20 model,

110
00:06:31.692 --> 00:06:34.892
defined as the presence of any two of the following parameters.

111
00:06:35.472 --> 00:06:38.712
They could have either an M spike more than two grams per deciliter, a light chain

112
00:06:38.772 --> 00:06:42.472
ratio more than 20, or bone marrow plasmacytosis of more than 20%.

113
00:06:43.452 --> 00:06:47.392
Or they could have the IMWG total risk score of nine or greater using

114
00:06:47.432 --> 00:06:49.432
the scoring system that's outlined on this slide.

115
00:06:50.772 --> 00:06:54.652
We also included patients that met very specific high-risk criteria that have

116
00:06:54.692 --> 00:06:56.292
previously been published,

117
00:06:57.312 --> 00:07:00.612
that included an evolving pattern, an abnormal plasma cell

118
00:07:00.652 --> 00:07:04.072
immunophenotype per the Patema criteria, high-risk cytogenetic

119
00:07:04.112 --> 00:07:08.032
abnormalities based on FISH, and then monoclonal light chain excretion of more than

120
00:07:08.052 --> 00:07:11.832
200 milligrams per 24 hours for those patients that have light chain smoldering

121
00:07:11.892 --> 00:07:12.431
myeloma.

122
00:07:14.672 --> 00:07:16.412
Here's the pertinent exclusion criteria.

123
00:07:16.452 --> 00:07:20.352
So anybody who met criteria for multiple myeloma based on the SLMM-CRAB criteria

124
00:07:20.392 --> 00:07:21.942
were, of course, excluded from this study.

125
00:07:22.732 --> 00:07:26.692
We also opted to exclude patients that had bone marrow plasmacytosis of more than

126
00:07:26.732 --> 00:07:27.352
40%.

127
00:07:28.232 --> 00:07:31.622
This was by design, since this study did not have any induction or bridging

128
00:07:31.692 --> 00:07:35.652
therapy, and this was the first trial looking at CAR T-cell therapy in this disease

129
00:07:35.722 --> 00:07:39.452
state. We wanted to exclude the patients that had high disease burden with the

130
00:07:39.532 --> 00:07:43.332
aim of limiting toxicities in this population.

131
00:07:45.252 --> 00:07:48.562
Here's the patient disposition. So 28 patients were assessed for eligibility.

132
00:07:48.952 --> 00:07:52.532
Twenty-two were approached, and ultimately, 20 patients received CAR T-cell

133
00:07:52.552 --> 00:07:54.792
therapy and remain in follow-up.

134
00:07:56.012 --> 00:07:59.392
And here's the study schema. So this study started initially with a six-patient

135
00:07:59.432 --> 00:08:03.172
safety run-in. We first started to look at a lower cilta-cel

136
00:08:03.252 --> 00:08:05.732
dose of 0.5 CAR T-cells per kilogram.

137
00:08:06.582 --> 00:08:09.852
And first three patients were treated at this dose with staggered enrollment.

138
00:08:10.752 --> 00:08:14.722
After this, there was a pre-planned safety pause and an FDA review, and then

139
00:08:14.812 --> 00:08:18.712
the dose was escalated to the standard dose of cilta-cel of 0.5 to

140
00:08:18.992 --> 00:08:22.181
1 CAR T-cells per kilogram, also with staggered enrollment.

141
00:08:23.032 --> 00:08:26.052
After these first six patients were treated, there was again a pre-planned safety

142
00:08:26.152 --> 00:08:29.592
pause and FDA review, and then the expansion cohort was opened at the

143
00:08:29.652 --> 00:08:32.252
0.5 to 1 CAR T-cell dose per kilogram.

144
00:08:33.793 --> 00:08:37.632
However, during the enrollment of this study, we were also learning in the relapse

145
00:08:37.653 --> 00:08:41.572
refractory myeloma patients that absolute lymphocyte count elevation

146
00:08:41.632 --> 00:08:45.412
can be associated with certain toxicities, in particular neurological toxicities.

147
00:08:46.021 --> 00:08:49.232
So we amended the protocol at this time and implemented an

148
00:08:49.292 --> 00:08:53.222
ALC-triggered prophylactic dexamethasone strategy as we now do for standard

149
00:08:53.252 --> 00:08:54.012
of care patients.

150
00:08:54.882 --> 00:08:58.332
At the same time, we lowered the dose of cilta-cel down to

151
00:08:58.372 --> 00:09:02.092
0.3 CAR T-cells per kilogram to really further optimize the

152
00:09:02.132 --> 00:09:03.172
risk-benefit ratio.

153
00:09:05.652 --> 00:09:06.992
Here are the patient characteristics.

154
00:09:07.072 --> 00:09:09.712
So in total, 20 patients were treated with cilta-cel.

155
00:09:10.232 --> 00:09:14.192
Twelve patients received a lower CAR T-cell dose at 0.3 to 0.5, and eight

156
00:09:14.272 --> 00:09:17.152
patients received more than 0.5 CAR T-cell dose.

157
00:09:17.972 --> 00:09:21.352
The median age was 58. You can see their laboratory parameters.

158
00:09:21.442 --> 00:09:25.372
So median M spike was 1.76 grams per deciliter, a light chain

159
00:09:25.392 --> 00:09:29.312
ratio of near 22, and bone marrow cell plasma infiltration of

160
00:09:29.492 --> 00:09:30.012
20%.

161
00:09:31.172 --> 00:09:35.072
Sixty-five percent of patients met high-risk criteria based on high-risk FISH

162
00:09:35.132 --> 00:09:39.032
abnormalities, and another 65% of patients also met high risk per

163
00:09:39.072 --> 00:09:40.192
the 20/2/20 model.

164
00:09:41.352 --> 00:09:45.172
In terms of screening to apheresis interval, it was 15 days, and

165
00:09:45.192 --> 00:09:48.002
that apheresis to infusion interval was 56 days in this

166
00:09:48.052 --> 00:09:49.332
study.

167
00:09:50.572 --> 00:09:51.972
Here's the overall safety profile.

168
00:09:52.012 --> 00:09:54.741
So no DLTs occurred in the safety run-in cohorts.

169
00:09:55.392 --> 00:09:59.212
CRS occurred in all patients, but no patients had Grade 3 or greater CRS

170
00:09:59.252 --> 00:10:03.241
events. Eighty-five percent of these cases were Grade 1 and 15% were Grade

171
00:10:03.452 --> 00:10:06.722
2. Tocilizumab was administered to 17 patients and

172
00:10:06.752 --> 00:10:10.402
dexamethasone to 13 patients, and this was all done using a low clinical

173
00:10:10.412 --> 00:10:12.822
threshold to prevent higher grade CRS events.

174
00:10:13.832 --> 00:10:17.772
Infectious events were all Grade 1 and 2 with no Grade 3 infections and

175
00:10:17.812 --> 00:10:21.232
mostly involved the upper respiratory tract, and all patients received

176
00:10:21.312 --> 00:10:22.752
IVIG prophylaxis.

177
00:10:24.352 --> 00:10:28.192
In terms of other toxicities, hematologic toxicities were common as expected

178
00:10:28.232 --> 00:10:30.752
with lymphodepleting chemotherapy and CAR T-cells.

179
00:10:30.792 --> 00:10:34.101
Ninety percent of patients had Grade 3 or greater neutropenia, but no incidents of

180
00:10:34.132 --> 00:10:37.392
febrile neutropenia, and all of these incidences resolved.

181
00:10:37.952 --> 00:10:41.872
And 15% of patients had Grade 3 or greater thrombocytopenia, also resolved, and no

182
00:10:41.912 --> 00:10:44.351
patients had any delayed hematologic toxicity.

183
00:10:45.472 --> 00:10:49.392
In terms of other non-heme toxicities, ALT Grade 3 or greater

184
00:10:49.452 --> 00:10:52.792
was increased in two patients in the context of CRS and also ultimately

185
00:10:52.832 --> 00:10:56.562
resolved. And notably, no patients had any evidence of ICANS in this

186
00:10:56.632 --> 00:11:00.532
study. However, we did see non-ICANS neurotoxicity

187
00:11:00.572 --> 00:11:02.782
or NINTs in seven patients, which I'll go over now.

188
00:11:04.832 --> 00:11:08.632
So these events, non-ICANS neurotoxicities, four of

189
00:11:08.672 --> 00:11:11.312
these were cranial nerve palsies, which is a known

190
00:11:12.132 --> 00:11:15.992
side effect of cilta-cel. Four out of these seven resolved completely, and the

191
00:11:16.032 --> 00:11:17.892
median time to onset was 21 days.

192
00:11:18.742 --> 00:11:21.872
Three patients had other ongoing NINTs at the time of data cutoff.

193
00:11:21.912 --> 00:11:25.092
Two of these patients had Grade 1 movement and neurocognitive symptoms.

194
00:11:25.872 --> 00:11:28.732
One of these patients, interestingly, had deposition of phosphorylated

195
00:11:28.812 --> 00:11:32.661
alpha-synuclein on a skin biopsy, suggesting a potential underlying

196
00:11:32.732 --> 00:11:34.392
predisposition to Parkinson's disease.

197
00:11:35.312 --> 00:11:38.762
And one patient had Grade 1 intention tremor during fine motor tasks without

198
00:11:38.792 --> 00:11:42.472
interference in daily living activities.

199
00:11:42.512 --> 00:11:44.492
Here are further details about these three patients.

200
00:11:44.692 --> 00:11:48.612
So all three of these patients experienced robust ALC expansion and

201
00:11:48.672 --> 00:11:51.292
had an elevation in their CD4 to CD8 ratio.

202
00:11:52.212 --> 00:11:56.032
Two out of these three patients received a higher CAR T-cell dose at more than 0.5

203
00:11:56.072 --> 00:11:59.702
CAR T-cells per kilogram, and one patient received a lower dose at 0.3.

204
00:12:00.792 --> 00:12:04.352
All of these patients received high-dose steroids and IVIG for management, and all

205
00:12:04.372 --> 00:12:07.572
three of them have had improvement in their symptoms and currently remain at Grade

206
00:12:07.832 --> 00:12:10.952
1 without interference of daily activities.

207
00:12:10.992 --> 00:12:14.452
One of these patients also received intrathecal chemotherapy, low dose

208
00:12:14.492 --> 00:12:18.352
ruxolitinib, and IV cyclophosphamide, not due to an increase in

209
00:12:18.452 --> 00:12:21.872
severity of symptoms, but really as a strategy to mitigate these

210
00:12:22.172 --> 00:12:26.114
symptoms altogether.So here's the efficacy

211
00:12:26.204 --> 00:12:30.164
data. So at a median follow-up of 15.3 months, all patients achieved MRD

212
00:12:30.204 --> 00:12:33.924
negativity at a sensitivity threshold of 10 to the minus six by next-generation

213
00:12:34.004 --> 00:12:37.104
sequencing, leading to 100% MRD negativity rate.

214
00:12:37.924 --> 00:12:41.764
The median time to MRD negativity was only one month, and all patients had MRD

215
00:12:41.824 --> 00:12:45.724
negativity at 10 to the minus five at one month, and at 10 to the minus six

216
00:12:45.764 --> 00:12:47.204
at two months post-infusion.

217
00:12:48.204 --> 00:12:51.864
MRD negativity was sustained in subsequent assessments in all patients through the

218
00:12:51.904 --> 00:12:52.544
data cutoff.

219
00:12:54.064 --> 00:12:57.704
In terms of IMWG response, all patients achieved an objective response leading to

220
00:12:57.764 --> 00:13:01.524
100% ORR, and 90% of these patients had a complete or

221
00:13:01.544 --> 00:13:05.204
stringent complete response. And in the remaining two patients, the follow-up is

222
00:13:05.214 --> 00:13:08.904
short at approximately 3.5 months, hence immunofixation remains

223
00:13:08.924 --> 00:13:11.664
positive, most likely due to slow clearance of residual paraprotein.

224
00:13:12.364 --> 00:13:16.164
And among 16 patients with at least six months of follow-up, all patients achieve

225
00:13:16.444 --> 00:13:17.664
stringent CR or CR.

226
00:13:18.604 --> 00:13:21.554
And you can see on the swimmer's plot, we have about 12 patients that have crossed

227
00:13:21.584 --> 00:13:25.504
the one-year mark, and all of these continue to have sustained MRD negativity

228
00:13:25.564 --> 00:13:26.024
at that time.

229
00:13:28.704 --> 00:13:31.184
Here is the progression-free survival and overall survival curves.

230
00:13:31.244 --> 00:13:34.704
So there have been no patients that have developed biochemical or

231
00:13:34.744 --> 00:13:38.684
SLIM-CLAP progression to date, and the median PFS and OS has not yet

232
00:13:38.724 --> 00:13:39.264
been reached.

233
00:13:41.464 --> 00:13:43.064
We also looked at some correlative analyses.

234
00:13:43.164 --> 00:13:47.004
So soluble BCMA after CAR T cell infusion declined rapidly,

235
00:13:47.044 --> 00:13:50.784
independent of dose, and fell below the median value of healthy controls by day

236
00:13:50.964 --> 00:13:54.884
21. Interestingly, baseline soluble BCMA did not

237
00:13:54.904 --> 00:13:58.744
correlate with an increased incidence of NINTs because we asked the question, since

238
00:13:58.764 --> 00:14:02.484
these patients did not receive any bridging or induction therapy, whether disease

239
00:14:02.524 --> 00:14:05.664
burden could have played a role in development of these toxicities, and at least

240
00:14:05.744 --> 00:14:09.044
based on the soluble BCMA level, this did not seem to be the case.

241
00:14:11.464 --> 00:14:15.364
Eighteen out of 20 patients had an absolute lymphocyte count of more than 3,000,

242
00:14:15.644 --> 00:14:18.854
and the median peak ALC across the cohort was almost 7,000.

243
00:14:19.584 --> 00:14:22.984
This was higher in patients that had a higher CAR T cell dose and also those that

244
00:14:23.004 --> 00:14:26.904
developed NINTs. I would point out, though, that majority of patients that had a

245
00:14:26.984 --> 00:14:30.964
lower CAR T cell dose also had preemptive dexamethasone that may have curbed

246
00:14:30.974 --> 00:14:34.644
the ALC expansion. And patients who developed NINTs showed greater

247
00:14:34.763 --> 00:14:38.524
post-infusion lymphocyte expansion with higher ALC exposure.

248
00:14:40.844 --> 00:14:44.104
In terms of CAR T cell expansion and subsets, CAR T cell expanded

249
00:14:44.664 --> 00:14:48.144
greater in patients that had a higher CAR T cell dose and also in those patients

250
00:14:48.204 --> 00:14:49.284
that had NINTs.

251
00:14:50.384 --> 00:14:54.134
CD4:CD8 ratio was broadly elevated across this entire study,

252
00:14:54.544 --> 00:14:58.504
did not differ over days 5 to 25 by dose group, but was higher in patients who

253
00:14:58.564 --> 00:15:00.564
developed NINTs compared to those that did not.

254
00:15:01.744 --> 00:15:05.524
And longitudinally, effector memory T cells remained high in the

255
00:15:05.564 --> 00:15:09.534
NINT positive patients, but declined in the low-dose group and

256
00:15:09.744 --> 00:15:12.564
NINT negative groups with reciprocal increases toward more terminally

257
00:15:12.604 --> 00:15:14.564
differentiated memory type states.

258
00:15:17.264 --> 00:15:20.644
So in conclusion, this is the first study of CAR T cell therapy in a precursor

259
00:15:20.684 --> 00:15:24.354
cancer setting where cilta-cel was used as a primary therapy with no

260
00:15:24.444 --> 00:15:28.204
induction or bridging therapy for patients with high-risk smoldering myeloma.

261
00:15:28.244 --> 00:15:31.984
There were no DLTs in the safety run-in cohort, and we saw no high-grade

262
00:15:32.044 --> 00:15:35.893
CRS events, ICHS, CAR T cell enterocolitis, delayed

263
00:15:35.904 --> 00:15:38.764
hematologic toxicities, nor any secondary cancers to date.

264
00:15:39.664 --> 00:15:43.564
Non-ICANS neurotoxicities, a known side effect of cilta-cel,

265
00:15:43.604 --> 00:15:47.104
was observed in seven patients. Four of these resolved completely, and three

266
00:15:47.204 --> 00:15:51.164
patients have mild symptoms with minimal impact on daily activities.

267
00:15:52.264 --> 00:15:55.914
All patients achieved MRD negativity at 10 to the minus six, and to our knowledge,

268
00:15:55.944 --> 00:15:59.584
it is the first time results like this have been seen in any disease

269
00:15:59.644 --> 00:16:01.504
state when it comes to plasma cell disorders.

270
00:16:02.044 --> 00:16:04.434
And MRD negativity remains sustained in all patients.

271
00:16:05.214 --> 00:16:08.844
No patients have progressed to active myeloma with a median of 15.3 months of

272
00:16:08.864 --> 00:16:12.544
follow-up. At the time of peak expansion, we saw mostly CD4

273
00:16:12.564 --> 00:16:16.444
positive CAR T cells, and patients with NINTs showed associations with higher

274
00:16:16.544 --> 00:16:18.104
ALC CAR T cell expansion

275
00:16:19.604 --> 00:16:23.224
with effector memory subtypes and an elevated CD4:CD8 ratio,

276
00:16:23.524 --> 00:16:26.264
with no association with baseline soluble BCMA.

277
00:16:27.224 --> 00:16:30.124
Longer follow-up is needed to determine the durability of response and help inform

278
00:16:30.164 --> 00:16:32.654
the risk-benefit ratio of early use of cilta-cel in this

279
00:16:32.724 --> 00:16:34.324
population.

280
00:16:35.144 --> 00:16:38.664
I'm pleased to share that our paper was just published today in "Nature Medicine,"

281
00:16:38.684 --> 00:16:41.824
and you can use this QR code to access it as it is open access.

282
00:16:41.844 --> 00:16:45.083
Here you'll find a lot more details about patients that were treated on this study.

283
00:16:46.744 --> 00:16:50.404
I want to end by thanking our entire study staff at Dana-Farber Cancer Institute

284
00:16:50.484 --> 00:16:54.004
who worked tirelessly on this study since 2022 when it first

285
00:16:54.264 --> 00:16:58.184
opened. I want to thank our study sponsor, Johnson &amp; Johnson, for supporting this

286
00:16:58.264 --> 00:17:01.744
study. Of course, the patients and their caregivers who really

287
00:17:02.524 --> 00:17:06.264
were phenomenal in enrolling into this trial, first of its kind, and really,

288
00:17:06.984 --> 00:17:10.315
I'm glad to see are benefiting with universal MRD negativity.

289
00:17:10.884 --> 00:17:14.305
I want to thank my co-first author, David Cordus Dos Santos, who was instrumental

290
00:17:14.325 --> 00:17:16.585
in putting the data analysis for this paper together.

291
00:17:17.244 --> 00:17:20.984
And last, but certainly not least, the senior author and my mentor, Irene Ghobrial.

292
00:17:21.785 --> 00:17:25.704
Her pursuit of achieving cure for this disease continues to lead to studies like

293
00:17:25.764 --> 00:17:29.284
this, and I'm forever grateful for working on her team. Thank you.

294
00:17:34.684 --> 00:17:37.324
Thank you very much, Dr. Nadeem. Very interesting

295
00:17:38.824 --> 00:17:40.644
experience with interception.

296
00:17:41.564 --> 00:17:45.324
To discuss this paper is Dr. Krina Patel

297
00:17:46.124 --> 00:17:47.684
from MD Anderson Cancer Center.

298
00:17:53.564 --> 00:17:57.064
Fantastic. Thank you to the chairs for this opportunity and to Dr.

299
00:17:57.184 --> 00:18:00.704
Nadeem for a fantastic trial that I get to now discuss and

300
00:18:00.944 --> 00:18:04.664
explain how I think of the data and how I would use it in my clinic in the

301
00:18:04.704 --> 00:18:08.324
future. So cilta-cel in high-risk smoldering multiple myeloma. Oh.

302
00:18:09.624 --> 00:18:13.084
Okay. I'm left-handed, so I do things backwards, so I apologize.

303
00:18:13.964 --> 00:18:17.424
So again, I think Dr. Nadeem did a great job with some of the introduction of what

304
00:18:17.444 --> 00:18:20.834
smoldering myeloma is. We're one of the few blood cancers,

305
00:18:21.524 --> 00:18:25.234
or any cancer, where we know someone has disease and likely is going to get that

306
00:18:25.244 --> 00:18:29.124
disease in the future, but because there's a huge delay in when they

307
00:18:29.164 --> 00:18:31.864
might get those symptoms, we actually watch patients.

308
00:18:31.904 --> 00:18:35.764
And most of this came from the fact that before, we couldn't really say we could

309
00:18:35.844 --> 00:18:39.516
cure myeloma.Today, we actually had a conference just a month

310
00:18:39.556 --> 00:18:43.516
ago to define what cure in myeloma means because of these novel therapies like

311
00:18:43.536 --> 00:18:47.516
bispecifics and CAR Ts. So I think we have the tools today, but we can

312
00:18:47.576 --> 00:18:51.526
always improve And so really high-risk smoldering myeloma in clinic, and in

313
00:18:51.556 --> 00:18:55.406
my clinic and many others, we don't still treat all patients, all

314
00:18:55.436 --> 00:18:58.816
high-risk smoldering myeloma, but we do actually offer it now.

315
00:18:58.986 --> 00:19:02.256
And there are certain patient populations, I will use things like monoclonal

316
00:19:02.356 --> 00:19:05.576
antibodies, and I'll go over some of those trials that we have.

317
00:19:05.616 --> 00:19:09.356
So really the question comes down to who truly has high-risk smoldering

318
00:19:09.376 --> 00:19:12.476
myeloma? And we're getting better with our clinical tools to define that.

319
00:19:12.996 --> 00:19:16.306
And then how aggressively should we treat those patients? Again, as Dr.

320
00:19:16.536 --> 00:19:20.476
Nadeem said, are we just trying to delay progression to actual myeloma, or are we

321
00:19:20.516 --> 00:19:23.996
trying to cure patients where they never need treatment for myeloma in the future?

322
00:19:25.136 --> 00:19:27.776
So these are our three big studies that we have in smoldering,

323
00:19:28.156 --> 00:19:31.996
historically. So the QREDIC study with len dex

324
00:19:32.056 --> 00:19:33.676
versus observation, the

325
00:19:34.596 --> 00:19:38.496
ECOG-E3A06 len versus observation, and again, the AKILA

326
00:19:38.536 --> 00:19:42.286
study most recently with our first immunotherapy trial, I guess, with

327
00:19:42.296 --> 00:19:44.216
daratumumab versus observation.

328
00:19:45.156 --> 00:19:49.136
And again, we can't really look at observation as a arm anymore if

329
00:19:49.156 --> 00:19:52.116
we were going to do a phase two study with um Celto cell.

330
00:19:52.796 --> 00:19:56.616
So the limitations on the last column for all these studies really are that the

331
00:19:56.776 --> 00:19:58.806
QREDIC study was in pre-modern imaging.

332
00:19:59.046 --> 00:20:02.976
So today we use MRIs to say if patients have lesions in their

333
00:20:02.996 --> 00:20:05.715
bone marrow that we would call it active myeloma.

334
00:20:05.796 --> 00:20:09.056
In the ECOG study, there was no overall survival conclusion.

335
00:20:09.166 --> 00:20:13.076
There was limited follow-up and again, PFS was different, but again, the

336
00:20:13.716 --> 00:20:16.576
population that we called smoldering was very different than what we do today.

337
00:20:17.276 --> 00:20:20.896
And then the AKILA study, again, progression outcomes were really

338
00:20:20.996 --> 00:20:23.496
CRAB criteria. They weren't active myeloma.

339
00:20:23.716 --> 00:20:27.466
So a lot of us, controversy in myeloma is what is active

340
00:20:27.536 --> 00:20:29.316
myeloma? Do we use slim CRAB,

341
00:20:30.196 --> 00:20:33.986
or do we say when patients end up having fractures or renal failure, those are real

342
00:20:34.016 --> 00:20:36.076
clinical outcomes that we want to prevent.

343
00:20:36.096 --> 00:20:39.916
So again, these are just some of the limitations that different folks have made in

344
00:20:39.936 --> 00:20:40.396
the past.

345
00:20:41.656 --> 00:20:45.256
And so again, coming back to who is high risk, I will say the easiest

346
00:20:45.316 --> 00:20:49.186
tool to say someone is high risk is the 20/2/20 model that

347
00:20:49.196 --> 00:20:51.976
Mayo initially started in 2018, and then the

348
00:20:52.036 --> 00:20:56.016
IMWG um validated. It's the easiest because I can do it in

349
00:20:56.036 --> 00:20:59.876
clinic really fast when I have a lot of patients, M protein greater than two, FLC

350
00:20:59.916 --> 00:21:02.816
ratio greater than 20, and bone marrow involvement greater than 20%.

351
00:21:03.436 --> 00:21:07.136
The issue is that in all the studies we had that I just showed historically

352
00:21:07.176 --> 00:21:10.916
didn't use this. And so again, AKILA, the daratumumab study, only

353
00:21:11.056 --> 00:21:14.516
40% of those patients actually would have fit this category of high-risk

354
00:21:14.616 --> 00:21:15.096
smoldering.

355
00:21:16.956 --> 00:21:20.886
So again, um I think our colleagues in the smoldering field have done a great job

356
00:21:20.916 --> 00:21:24.506
of trying to really include all the different parts of why somebody would

357
00:21:24.696 --> 00:21:28.536
relapse within two years or not, or have newly diagnosed myeloma within two

358
00:21:28.556 --> 00:21:31.956
years. But this is what we have. These are all the different iterations of

359
00:21:31.976 --> 00:21:34.126
different classifications for high-risk smoldering.

360
00:21:34.576 --> 00:21:38.506
And so again, in the end, currently, most of us use that last one, which is

361
00:21:38.536 --> 00:21:42.466
the IMWG 2020 with cytogenetic um involvement.

362
00:21:43.016 --> 00:21:47.006
And so um you know again, these are patients who are 44% to 63%

363
00:21:47.036 --> 00:21:49.356
chance of having myeloma at two years.

364
00:21:49.396 --> 00:21:53.326
So again, because of that variation, different patients have different preferences,

365
00:21:53.476 --> 00:21:56.916
and so why most of us don't treat all high-risk patients um as of right

366
00:21:56.956 --> 00:22:00.876
now. So having said that, if someone in front of me

367
00:22:01.056 --> 00:22:04.076
knew that they were about to have myeloma, even if it was going to be five years

368
00:22:04.136 --> 00:22:07.856
from now, but we could say we could cure it, I think that would change that

369
00:22:08.056 --> 00:22:11.976
discussion of risk benefit. And so again, I think durable treatment,

370
00:22:12.196 --> 00:22:16.136
free control is one way to look at um possible cure

371
00:22:16.176 --> 00:22:19.116
and MRD negativity, sustained off therapy.

372
00:22:19.176 --> 00:22:22.626
Haven't yet demonstrated that with any of our prior treatments like lenalidomide or

373
00:22:22.676 --> 00:22:26.176
daratumumab, but here you saw the data and looks pretty fantastic.

374
00:22:26.796 --> 00:22:29.876
Um and also prevention of those clinically meaningful events.

375
00:22:29.936 --> 00:22:33.136
Again, my patients don't get renal failure. They don't get fractures.

376
00:22:33.476 --> 00:22:37.096
They don't get major infections. That is huge for their mortality as well as their

377
00:22:37.136 --> 00:22:37.716
morbidity.

378
00:22:39.476 --> 00:22:43.276
Um and again, we talked about this a little bit, but not all progression events are

379
00:22:43.316 --> 00:22:47.246
equal. And so we know that about 14% to 40% of patients

380
00:22:48.096 --> 00:22:51.856
um only have slim events, and so are we really making a difference when we're

381
00:22:51.896 --> 00:22:54.916
treating patients and intervening um at that smoldering stage?

382
00:22:55.656 --> 00:22:57.745
The other question that comes up is resistance.

383
00:22:58.196 --> 00:23:01.826
When we're treating patients with len or dara, a lot of us think that, well, if

384
00:23:01.876 --> 00:23:05.556
this patient ends up with myeloma in three, four years, can I use my upfront

385
00:23:05.596 --> 00:23:09.416
therapies? Because we usually use a quadruplet, dara, len, bortezomib, dex.

386
00:23:10.096 --> 00:23:13.856
CAR T, we don't use in front line, and resistance mechanisms are very

387
00:23:13.876 --> 00:23:17.316
different. Um we don't think that we have resistance to other therapies, but

388
00:23:17.336 --> 00:23:20.456
again, right now we only do it in really relapsed refractory patients.

389
00:23:20.856 --> 00:23:24.796
So what would happen if we intervened early on and someone does get myeloma, how

390
00:23:24.836 --> 00:23:27.956
am I going to treat that afterwards? So unknown questions.

391
00:23:28.776 --> 00:23:32.736
And then looking at toxicity. So again, with len, grade three, four

392
00:23:33.176 --> 00:23:35.736
non-hematologic toxicities was about 28%.

393
00:23:36.216 --> 00:23:39.276
Many patients came off those studies um because of side effects.

394
00:23:39.356 --> 00:23:41.136
Because again, these patients are asymptomatic.

395
00:23:41.536 --> 00:23:45.156
We're giving them something that causes symptoms, so people do tend to come off

396
00:23:45.216 --> 00:23:48.476
study sometimes. With dara, grade three, four infections were about

397
00:23:48.496 --> 00:23:52.346
16% and 4.6% discontinuation. With

398
00:23:52.376 --> 00:23:54.176
CAR T, we haven't had anyone come off study.

399
00:23:54.236 --> 00:23:57.156
It's a one and done, so it's a little bit harder to say I'm coming off study for

400
00:23:57.176 --> 00:24:00.636
side effects. But you know we heard a little bit about CRS and ICANS.

401
00:24:00.696 --> 00:24:02.806
Those are not things that we worry about so much anymore.

402
00:24:03.236 --> 00:24:07.026
But sometimes things like prolonged cytopenias, other infections long

403
00:24:07.116 --> 00:24:10.816
term, or even risk of IEC colitis, which again, we haven't seen in

404
00:24:10.826 --> 00:24:14.116
studies. This study didn't have it, but in the real world, some of our patients are

405
00:24:14.136 --> 00:24:16.536
getting some of these autoimmune type side effects.

406
00:24:16.556 --> 00:24:19.316
So something that we need to think about as we have more patients

407
00:24:19.416 --> 00:24:22.832
treated.And so, but again, the data's

408
00:24:22.872 --> 00:24:25.362
fantastic. You can't go above 100%, right?

409
00:24:25.772 --> 00:24:29.592
100% overall response rate, flat curves, MRD at 10th and minus

410
00:24:29.692 --> 00:24:31.892
six, which is the best we can do in myeloma right now.

411
00:24:32.302 --> 00:24:34.612
And that PFS and overall just being a straight line.

412
00:24:34.892 --> 00:24:37.852
Again, there's no extra credit. You can't go above 100%.

413
00:24:37.932 --> 00:24:41.572
So this is just phenomenal data, and I think really important for our

414
00:24:41.632 --> 00:24:45.472
field to know that when we go earlier, we can do better for our patients.

415
00:24:46.052 --> 00:24:48.812
And of course, the risk then comes to that toxicity.

416
00:24:49.252 --> 00:24:52.992
The hematologic toxicity in heme, we don't really mind, and most of our patients do

417
00:24:53.051 --> 00:24:56.992
well. Late line, our patients do have significant toxicities where we've had to

418
00:24:57.212 --> 00:25:01.192
give patients stem cells back because of their continued delayed cytopenias.

419
00:25:01.232 --> 00:25:04.492
In early relapse, we don't see that as much, and so I have a feeling that in

420
00:25:04.532 --> 00:25:08.381
smoldering we wouldn't see that either because patients are not as heavily treated.

421
00:25:09.512 --> 00:25:13.052
I think the major toxicity here that we would talk about is that non-ICANS

422
00:25:13.072 --> 00:25:15.252
neurotoxicity. So again, it was

423
00:25:16.232 --> 00:25:18.832
a small number of patients, seven, that had this.

424
00:25:18.872 --> 00:25:22.812
Three of those had cranial nerve palsies, which we do see in patients who get

425
00:25:22.872 --> 00:25:26.512
relapse refractory setting of CAR T, and those are

426
00:25:26.752 --> 00:25:29.632
usually pretty reversible with IVIG and dex.

427
00:25:29.692 --> 00:25:32.922
But when patients have movement disorders, when it affects their

428
00:25:32.952 --> 00:25:36.732
potential in terms of being kind of normal for the rest of their

429
00:25:36.752 --> 00:25:39.582
life, we do worry about that. And that is a big side effect we talk to our

430
00:25:39.652 --> 00:25:42.412
patients. And I think one of the questions that I would have for Dr.

431
00:25:42.612 --> 00:25:46.492
Nadeem is we saw that ALC increase, and we know those are the patients

432
00:25:46.532 --> 00:25:50.252
that are higher likely to get these toxicities.

433
00:25:50.472 --> 00:25:52.792
Do we intervene at that time point? Do we give steroids?

434
00:25:52.812 --> 00:25:55.972
Do we do something to turn that volume down to see if we can improve these

435
00:25:56.012 --> 00:25:59.732
toxicities? Because again, if we didn't have that, I would say this was a

436
00:25:59.752 --> 00:26:00.592
complete home run.

437
00:26:01.512 --> 00:26:05.232
And so coming back, is cure possible before having significant

438
00:26:05.272 --> 00:26:09.212
symptoms from myeloma? This is in patients who had six lines of therapy, so

439
00:26:09.272 --> 00:26:12.972
really relapse refractory. To have 33% being five years

440
00:26:13.092 --> 00:26:16.952
out, and again, the basis of the definition of cure for myeloma

441
00:26:16.972 --> 00:26:20.832
is pretty phenomenal. But I think the question is, are we going to have a

442
00:26:20.872 --> 00:26:24.552
line that goes across the whole 100% for our smoldering patients?

443
00:26:24.932 --> 00:26:28.452
What does that line need to be? And then again, how long do we need it?

444
00:26:28.592 --> 00:26:32.572
Is five years functional cure enough for our smoldering patients, or do we want 10

445
00:26:32.612 --> 00:26:35.472
years to be, or our patients never getting

446
00:26:36.952 --> 00:26:39.852
myeloma as the definition of cure in smoldering myeloma.

447
00:26:40.312 --> 00:26:43.392
So again, we'll finally be able to talk about these things because we have data

448
00:26:43.452 --> 00:26:46.852
like this. And so my last couple of slides, I think the four critical questions

449
00:26:46.932 --> 00:26:48.952
really are, who are the right patients?

450
00:26:48.992 --> 00:26:52.732
Who are those patients that truly are going to have myeloma, that by intervening,

451
00:26:52.832 --> 00:26:56.672
we're actually changing their outcomes? Can we cure them?

452
00:26:56.772 --> 00:27:00.182
Can we have durable control? Are we preventing meaningful

453
00:27:00.212 --> 00:27:04.172
events? And again, is that risk-benefit acceptable for patients who

